, United Kingdom","Kinghorn, Fife, Scotland":"Kinghorn, Fife, Skotland"},"nl":{"13 Apr 1578–":"13 april 1578–Overleden","1578–Female":"1578–Overleden","1587–Male":"1587–Overleden","1590–Male":"1590–Overleden","1614–Male":"1614–Overleden","1560–Male":"1560–Overleden","about 1590":"circa 1590","1578":"1578","9 January 1614":"9 januari 1614","1587":"1587","1560":"1560","1590":"1590","13 Apr 1578":"13 april 1578","1614":"1614","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kinghorn, Fife, Scotland":"Kinghorn, Fife, Schotland"},"en":{"13 Apr 1578–":"13 April 1578–Deceased","1578–Female":"1578–Deceased","1587–Male":"1587–Deceased","1590–Male":"1590–Deceased","1614–Male":"1614–Deceased","1560–Male":"1560–Deceased","about 1590":"about 1590","1578":"1578","9 January 1614":"9 January 1614","1587":"1587","1560":"1560","1590":"1590","13 Apr 1578":"13 April 1578","1614":"1614","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland, United Kingdom","Kinghorn, Fife, Scotland":"Kinghorn, Fife, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Portous","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): variant of   Porteous  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Porteous","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname from Middle English and Older Scots <i>port(e)hors</i>, <i>portas</i>, <i>porte(i)s</i>, <i>portos</i>, <i>portus</i>, <i>porthous</i>, <i>porteus</i>, <i>portewas</i> ‘portable breviary, prayer book’. It is a borrowing of Old French <i>porte-hors</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>porteose</i>, <i>porteho(r)s</i>, <i>port(h)eus</i>, literally something ‘carried out of doors’. The surname may have been given to someone who habitually carried such a book, or for a scribe employed to write them. In modern times it is chiefly a Scottish surname, which probably accounts for its presence in northern England, but the name is also well evidenced in southeastern England in the medieval period and in northern Lincolnshire since the 17th century. The Scottish surname became established in Ireland by the mid 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Nanis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and English: a medieval vernacular form of   Agnes  , which gave rise to a surname. Its modern use as a given name is probably at least in part a transferred use of the surname as well as a revival of the medieval given name."],"variants":[{"name":"Annice","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Annis  , based on the numerous women's names ending in <i>-ice</i>."]},{"name":"Annys","meanings":["and English: a medieval vernacular form of   Agnes  , which gave rise to a surname. Its modern use as a given name is probably at least in part a transferred use of the surname as well as a revival of the medieval given name."]}]},{"name":"Marion","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a medieval French diminutive form of   Marie  , introduced to Britain in the Middle Ages. In some places it was taken as a pet form of   Margaret   or   Margery .  As a male name, it is an altered form of the Continental male name <i>Marian</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>Marianus</i> (from   Marius  ), but is now rarely, if ever, used. It was the birth name of the American film star  John Wayne  (  1907–79 )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Nanis Marion Agnes Portous was christened on 13 April 1578, in Kinghorn, Fife, Scotland as the daughter of William Portous. She had at least 2 sons with James Liberton Greg."},"et":{"13 Apr 1578–":"13. aprill 1578–Surnud","1578–Female":"1578–Surnud","1587–Male":"1587–Surnud","1590–Male":"1590–Surnud","1614–Male":"1614–Surnud","1560–Male":"1560–Surnud","about 1590":"umbes 1590","1578":"1578","9 January 1614":"9. jaanuar 1614","1587":"1587","1560":"1560","1590":"1590","13 Apr 1578":"13. aprill 1578","1614":"1614","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Kinghorn, Fife, Scotland":"Kinghorn, Fife, Scotland"},"fi":{"13 Apr 1578–":"13. huhtikuuta 1578–Kuollut","1578–Female":"1578–Kuollut","1587–Male":"1587–Kuollut","1590–Male":"1590–Kuollut","1614–Male":"1614–Kuollut","1560–Male":"1560–Kuollut","about 1590":"noin 1590","1578":"1578","9 January 1614":"9. tammikuuta 1614","1587":"1587","1560":"1560","1590":"1590","13 Apr 1578":"13. huhtikuuta 1578","1614":"1614","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kinghorn, Fife, Scotland":"Kinghorn, Fife, Scotland"},"fr":{"13 Apr 1578–":"13 avril 1578–Décédée","1578–Female":"1578–Décédée","1587–Male":"1587–Décédé","1590–Male":"1590–Décédé","1614–Male":"1614–Décédé","1560–Male":"1560–Décédé","about 1590":"environ 1590","1578":"1578","9 January 1614":"9 janvier 1614","1587":"1587","1560":"1560","1590":"1590","13 Apr 1578":"13 avril 1578","1614":"1614","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Kinghorn, Fife, Scotland":"Kinghorn, Fife, Écosse","lifeSummary":"Nanis Marion Agnes Portous a été baptisée le 1